A version of the third isomorphism theorem: if G₂ ≤ G and H' is a subgroup of G⧸G₂, then there
is a canonical isomorphism between H⧸H' and G⧸N, where N is the preimage of H' in G. A bit clunky;
may be a better way to do this

In fact $k$ is at most
 $$ \delta + \frac{\eta}{6} \sum_{i=1}^2 \sum_{1 \leq j,l \leq 3; j \neq l}
     (d[X^0_i;T_j|T_l] - d[X^0_i; X_i]).$$

$k$ is at most
$$ \leq I(U : V \, | \, S) + I(V : W \, | \,S) + I(W : U \, | \, S) + \frac{\eta}{6}
\sum_{i=1}^2 \sum_{A,B \in \{U,V,W\}: A \neq B} (d[X^0_i;A|B,S] - d[X^0_i; X_i]).$$

With the notation of the previous lemma, we have
  \begin{equation}\label{5.3-conv}
    k - D[ X'_{[m]} | Y_{[m]} ] \leq \eta \sum_{i=1}^m d[X_{\sigma(i)};X'_i|Y_i]
  \end{equation}
for any permutation $\sigma : \{1,\dots,m\} \rightarrow \{1,\dots,m\}$.
